OL,6,FAid is classified largely as day-to-
OL,7,Fday operational expenditure whereas
OL,8,Fmuch of defence is capital. And since
OL,9,Fthe primary binding fiscal rule is to
OL,10,Fbalance day-to-day spending with tax
OL,11,Frevenues, cutting development spending
OL,12,Fby #6 billion generates #6 billion of
OL,13,Fheadroom, even when that #6 billion
OL,14,Fgoes to the Ministry of Defence to
OL,15,Fspend on planes and ships.
OL,17,FYou may at this juncture have
OL,18,Fconcluded that the fiscal rules, far
OL,19,Ffrom being Solomonic wisdom, are in
OL,20,Ffact nuts, too nutty even to grace the
OL,21,Fpages of Alice or Rachel in Wonderland.
